BACTERIAL CANKER, KIWIFRUIT - NEW ZEALAND
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: 20 Nov 2010
Source: Biosecurity New Zealand [edited]
<http://www.biosecurity.govt.nz/media/20-11-10/new-Zealand-pollen-tests-positive-for-Psa>


Biosecurity New Zealand (Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry, MAF)
announced this afternoon [20 Nov 2010] that samples of New Zealand
pollen have tested positive for the bacterial kiwifruit disease,
_Pseudomonas syringae_ pv. _actinidiae_ (Psa). Positive results from
2009 and 2010 and "weak" positive results from 2007 indicate that Psa
may have been present in New Zealand for a number of years. The
samples pre-date imported pollen.

Imported Chilean pollen produced a "weak" positive result on a single
sample. The implications of this result are still unclear; however,
testing of historical samples suggests that this pollen may not be
the original source of infection.

There is no current evidence to show that Psa in pollen can infect
healthy kiwifruit vines. MAF's initial analysis shows that many
infected orchards have not used artificial pollination, suggesting
other mechanisms of spread. [However,] MAF cautioned growers on the
use of artificial pollination. Pollen collected in the same orchard
presents a lower risk than pollen sourced from another property.

--
