******
[4]
Date: 19 Nov 2010
Source: Sunlive [edited]
<http://www.sunlive.co.nz/news/9590-infected-vines-to-be-torched.html>


MAF Biosecurity has announced burning of infected kiwifruit vines is
due to start at a special incineration zone. MAF Psa infection
response manager David Yard says a never before used incineration
machine will burn the infected vines. The air curtain incinerator was
originally purchased by the department for the disposal of animal
carcasses if there was an outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease [FMD] in
New Zealand.

[Byline: Lyle McMahon]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Bacterial canker of kiwifruit (_Actinidia_ species and hybrids)
caused by _Pseudomonas syringae_ pv. _actinidiae_ was originally
described in Japan in 1989, but its area of origin is uncertain.
Symptoms include discolouration of buds and vascular tissues, leaf
spots, wilting, stem and twig cankers with characteristic red
exudate, fruit collapse, and eventually death of the plant. The
disease is favoured by cool temperatures and high humidity, thus
symptoms are usually seen in spring and autumn.

Data on epidemiology are still lacking, but infection is thought to
occur via natural leaf openings and wounds. The pathogen is suspected
to be spread by heavy rain, strong winds, mechanical means (including
animal and human activities), and infected planting material. Spread
with infected fruit and/or pollen cannot be excluded until conclusive
data become available.

Generally, disease management of bacterial diseases may include
cultural practices, crop rotation, phytosanitation to prevent spread,
use of clean planting material and resistant crop varieties, but
specific control strategies for kiwi canker are being developed.
Chemical control (copper compounds, antibiotics) is used in Japan,
but resistant pathogen strains have emerged.

It is thought that a recent outbreak in Italy (ProMED-mail post
20100414.1207) affecting 25 percent of the Zespri Gold variety vines
may have been due to the emergence of a new strain. The strains
present in New Zealand still remain to be identified.

